When I see reviews that say "I would give 10 stares if I could" you can insert over exaggerated eye roll from me. However, after my dining experience (yes, it was an EXPERIENCE) at thee Gary Dankos, I have now become one of those persons. Okay, the door person right on que. the hostess effortlessly finds my reservation advises I am the first to arrive in my party (this never happens, me the first to arrive that is. I was excited) She invites me to have a seat at the bar, I happily take her up on the offer. I'm not kidding as soon as I sit down another well trained staff member shows up to assist with scooting my stool closer to the counter. A bartender appeared to take my order of crisp sparkling Prosecco "Alice" Im Pretty sure that's not the name but it's close. It was the most refreshing glass of cold sparkling Prosecco ever. The other half of my reservation showed. The hostess took her jacket. A male host advised he would take care of transporting my Prosecco and escorted us to our table. As we were seated he also offered to take our purses and store them out of the way. So convenient! Another person showed up and reviewed the menu and the ordering process with us. You can order from either the left or right side of the menu. The left side is a choice of 5 different items including deserts. You can order 5 lobster if you like or you can spread it out to have a sensibly balanced meal. As tempting as it was to order 5 desserts I went with the following soup(sorry I can't remember what kind it was) it was a delicious 5 teaspoonful dish of something. My second choice was a crab mango salad. This was just as delicious as the crab salad served at Ruth's Chris. No disappointment here and it was a regular size serving. Third was the lobster so tender and layered with flavor served over a creamy buttery mashed potato with chives Fourth was the filet Mignon served with a reduction of onion and I want to say a balsamic of some kind. It was amazing. The persons at the table next to us wanted to know what it was. Uhmmm delicious goodness ma'am. Last but not least dessert they do not make these choices easy! I finally decided to go with a trio of crime brûlée 3 flavors Ginger, Maple and Vanilla I think? Each one was wonderful it was like having three desserts in one. We also received a complementary assortment of like 9 mini desserts bites..Pecan, coconut, lemon meringue , chocolate mousse, lemon gel square(?) we were so full we could not eat another bite (pun intended) so I don't know what the other 3 were. We also had a second glass of Prosecco. Our total before tip was 380. We didn't even blink it was worth every penny, I can't wait for the next visit. If you haven't gone yet and you've heard or wondered about Gary Dankos allow yourself the extravagant splurge GO! You will thank yourself for the treat. If I could give 10 stars I seriously would. Impeccable service and food you must experience.

Gary Danko is definitely one of the best restaurants in the Bay Area and recognized as such. Great food and service. The other thing I like is that they allow you the flexibility to order what you like. So if I choose the 5 course menu, I can have 3 appetizers if I want to and two mains. No need to order dessert if I don't want to. There's a lot of choices on the menu so this kind of flexibility makes a lot of sense. It's a place that I definitely would recommend to friends and people I know. Lastly, having been to many highly rated restaurants, I'd say that Gary Danko is good value. It's very reasonably priced for this kind of quality and standard.

Restaurant Gary Danko was delicious and you won't leave hungry. We got the three course meal for $89. I had the (1) risotto with rock shrimp, crab, asparagus and beech mushrooms, (2) roast main lobster, and (3) filet of beef with potato gnocchi. My boyfriend had the (1) Coconut Thai curry with shrimp, calamari, lobster, scallops, and mushrooms, (2) filet of beef, and (3) creme fraiche cheesecake. We had two drinks each and the bill with tip, taxes, and whatever else CA and SF add ended up around $350. So know what you're getting into before you go so that you don't have a horrible surprise when you leave! I like that you can customize your 3, 4, or 5 courses - choosing from any section of the menu. Meaning, you could get 4 options from the dessert section or 3 filets of beef if you so choose. I'm not a dessert person and was thrilled to not be forced to have that as a course as so many other places do. They will modify the portion sizing depending on what you are ordering. So if you get two appetizers and a filet, the filet will be larger in size than if you were to get two other meat options with the filet. In my opinion, the gnocchi was the best thing I tasted. I would have preferred all gnocchi and no filet! The steak was okay. My boyfriend who is not as into food as I am raved about the cheesecake and actually called his meal "out of this world." A phrase I don't believe I've ever heard him utter. We were happy with the portion sizes - its not like the commercial of the couple who go to the fancy restaurant and have to stop at the convenience store on the way home to get more food. But, considering you're paying $30 for each course, you should be full! Nice touch to send everyone home with a wonderful pineapple sponge cake for the next day. Delicious!! No jacket required for men, but dress up anyways and have a great night out!

As a visitor to San Francisco, I've been to Gary Danko two or three times before, and have always found it to be an excellent restaurant, and a pretty remarkable value. On my most recent visit, they just blew me away. I was in the City with my wife and our grandson, celebrating his ninth birthday. We decided to go to Gary Danko at the last minute, and they could not have been more accommodating. We had to go early (5:30), but they gave us the best table in the house, a booth facing the main dining area that was spacious and quiet. Our grandson is a bit precocious, to say the least, and they could not have responded to him any better. The entire wait staff was gracious, patient and delightful. For him, it was the highlight of a five-day trip. It was a highlight for us, too! The food was wonderful, as always, and the service, impeccable and extraordinary as described above. I really appreciate how you can choose several ways of enjoying the cuisine - ala carte, or a 3,4 or 5-course tasting menu, with or without wine pairings. Many other fine restaurants restrict your choices - because they can. At Gary Danko, they could get away with doing the same, but they don't, and i really think highly of them for losing the 'attitude.' I doubt I'll ever return to San Francisco without dining at Gary Danko, it's just too good to miss!

What else is there to say? Everything at Gary Danko is top of the line. Service, ambiance, and food. My date and I each did a four course meal. She went with the risotto, scallops, lobster and cheese and I went with the poached egg, lobster, beef, and soufflé. Hands down the best dining experience I've had.

One of the best dining experiences EVER. My expectations were pretty high going in as we were able to dine at Daniel in NYC earlier this year and I was also a little weary of the prior reviews that mentioned Danko maybe slipping a little bit. My verdict? Nothing short of FANTASTIC. Bookmark this restaurant and make a reservation for your next trip in SF. That being said, reservations may be hard to come by. The booking window opens 2 months (not 60 days) prior to the date you are looking for. The difference of 2 months vs 60 days is huge because it means you may or may not get in at the date/time you prefer. The best way to make reservations is to call right the restaurant directly. Danko is on OpenTable, however they offer very limited slots via OpenTable. Also, be sure to note a special occasions upon making your reservation. We arrived and checked in with the hostess. We were a little early and started our evening at the bar. The cocktail menu is comprised of classic drinks, I had a Kir Royale and my bf had a Manhattan, both perfectly crafted. The restaurant is a good size with an intimate and romantic feel. After moving to our table, we made our dinner selections. There a few different ways you can order, either Chef's tasting menu ($128 for 5 courses with optional $95 wine pairings) or choose your own from their extensive options of appetizers, seafood, meat, and dessert. If you choose your own, you can pick 3 courses ($89), 4 courses ($109), or 5 courses ($128). They also don't limit the types of courses you can get, so you can order all entrees or all desserts if you wanted. Wine pairings are not offered if you select your own courses. Both my bf and I selected 5 courses and between the two of us we had: - seared foie gras with caramelized onions and apples - dungeness crab salad with avocado, citrus, quinoa - seared ahi with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms - porcini and mushroom bique - branzini with fennel puree and nicoise olives - seared scallop with butternut fondue, braised leeks, carrot-parsnip puree - herb crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, medjool dates, rainbow carrots, and green chermoula - juniper crusted bison with trumpet mushrooms, cipollini mushrooms, and herb spatzle - artisanal cheese course (you pick 4 from their cart) and served with raisin bread and fruit - grand marnier souffle with blood orange sorbet - bonus dessert : chocolate tart, presented for our anniversary AND IT WAS ALLLLL DELICIOUS!! I'll spare the nitty gritties of each dish and just say that each dish was cooked to perfection, well balanced and seasoned. The dishes that stood out to me most were the porcini bisque, lamb, and bison...probably only because it's not something you come across on every menu. Their menu is also always changing, so it can be hard to order based on recommended dishes mentioned in reviews. I think the best way to enjoy your dining experience is to share bites from each other like we did so that you are able to try a little bit of everything. If you normally have a pretty healthy appetite, you will have no issues with 5 courses. There are also a few extras in between in the courses like the amuse-bouche, bread service, and a cake for you take home for breakfast. The service was also flawless, with wine flowing and waters always full. A few things I'd also like to mention... 1. While I am an avid Yelper and normally make my bf wait so I can snap photos of our meal before we eat, please put your phone away and just enjoy your experience and the company you are with. The only reason I even took a photo of my souffle was because of its amazing height (though hard to see). The couple that was seated next us were THOSE people as the gf insisted on 5 different photos of just her and her first course and then proceeded to photograph her bf and his dish. It's one thing to take a quick photo, but don't be a distraction and have a full on photo shoot 2. The dining experience at Gary Danko is slightly less formal than other Michelin-star, fine dining restaurants (like Daniel) so one cannot make equal comparisons. I would consider the attire to be business casual because let's be real, we're in Cali. I also noticed they don't implement a couple service nuances (like synchronized service), which makes the experience less formal, not a bad thing, just an observation 3. I did not think portions were small as mentioned in the couple reviews I read. I actually thought each dish was a pretty fair portion for fine dining and considering that dinner is multiple courses 4. When you are leaving, you can ask for a copy of the menu from that night's service. It's presented in a gold envelope and signed by Chef Danko, makes for a great keepsake :)

Exquisite. Can't wait for my next trip to San Francisco. The location was good too. Hopefully they can expand to other cities as well.

Delicious and interesting meal. Presentation and service were wonderful. We will visit again!

Gary Danko is our go-to special occasion dinner. The service is exquisite, and the risotto appetizer and cheese cart blow me away every time. We also love the flambé dessert prepared table side, and one of us gets it every time. Hooray for Gary Danko!

The G-Dank is arguably San Francisco's most quintessential fine dining experience. You select among a 3/4/5 course menu, respectively priced at $83/$101/$119. The best part is that you have the flexibility to pick any combination of dishes your heart desires. So yes, you can totally go all out and only choose entrees. For folks who can't make up their minds, GD offers a 5 course tasting menu composed of the restaurant's signature dishes. Either way, be sure to come hungry as portions here are quite sizable. Personal favorites for each course include the glazed oysters, roast Maine lobster, and seared filet of beef. For my fellow cheese heads, taking a crack at their farmhouse and artisinal selection is also mandatory. Dishes that I would skip next time are the roasted quail and chocolate soufflé. I have tried a few Michelin star restaurants, however this was the only one I have visited on multiple of occasions. The food and service definitely justifies the cost, which is reasonable when you take in account the portion size of the dishes. You can always go with the chef's pre fixe menu for 5 dishes or choose your own between 3,4, or 5 pre fixe items from the menu. I always go with 4 items and by the end of the night, I'm beyond stuffed. That allows me to choose one item from each section, "appetizers", "fish and seafood", "meat and bird", and finally "dessert". However, you can mix it up in whichever way you would like. Two must try items would be the seared foie gras and the trio creme brûlée. Otherwise, I would also suggest the selection of cheese tableside for the experience. It's a great experience every time, if you are looking for a Michelin star restaurant to visit for the first time, I would suggest Gary Danko. It will definitely help you with setting standards high and expectations that you should hold for other restaurants.

Just like any other Yelper, I have been putting off going to this popular restaurant in the city FOREVER, because there are too many other good fine dining spots around. I finally got around to going the other night since I was in the city at the time and we got pretty lucky with just walking in and no reservations. Gary Danko is located on North Point Street in the Russian Hill neighborhood of San Francisco. It's in a very touristy area (by Fisher's Wharf.) so I was kind of put off by that piece of information. The parking situation isn't very good because of that. You might have to drive around for a while trying to find a spot or you can always use their valet service at the front entrance for a fee of $20. I think I may have been spoiled by the many other fine dining establishments I've tried, but for some reason, I just wasn't blown away by the food and cocktails. I was expecting more from a restaurant with a Michelin Star and an average of 4 1/2 stars. Don't get me wrong, I do think the value is great when it comes to price versus amount. Customers can pick from ordering a 3, 4, or 5 course Tasting Menu and they can also customize whichever dishes they want i.e. 1 appetizer and 2 entrées without dessert. They also give a extra dessert if customers are celebrating a special event. On top of that, they also send over an extra plate of mini desserts. When you are given the bill at the end of the night, you are also given their special house-made cake to take home with you. The service at the restaurant was good. I saw servers doing the "sweeping" of the tables often throughout the night. While I did taste each dish and finished each morsel of food on the plates, it felt like food I could've ordered at any other American restaurant. It just didn't seem that refined to me although it was good. None of the flavors were creative or innovative, even the Soufflé which I was eagerly waiting for at the end of the meal was too dense (cakey) and completely deflated within seconds. For the price we paid, I would probably rather pick to go dine at Alexander's Steakhouse. Their light and airy Soufflés just can't be replicated. Overall, I was glad I finally got the chance to dine at Gary Danko. I would go back if we had any events to celebrate with friends. (Seems like each table was celebrating something.)

Here's the deal. The food- amazing the wait staff- even more amazing. The decor and space between tables is a serious problem. I mean, I was entertained by the very awkward first date to the left of me and the table of very cheap men complaining about the bill to the right of me (how do I know this? Because the tables are so close together, there is no privacy and I heard every conversation) but I mean, I didn't come here for that kind of entertainment. It's also oddly loud. The restaurant is in desperate need of a revamping. It's VERY clean, just dated. It's time, Gary. 6 stars to the food and wait staff. 3 stars for decor and atmosphere.

Gary Danko has been on my bucket list, oh for, about 17 years, 32 days...and it did not disappoint. I expected a stop by the taco truck on the way home, but this is NOT a pretentious, fluffy, restaurant in which basil foam on braised cherry tomato on a large platter is presented to you. This was REAL food, with, for example, Demi glacé made from roasting bones, ingredients that are highlighted in its own glory and not hidden in sauces, but paired well with other ingredients to enhance the main event, with 50 pages of wine listed by regions to choose from and a well orchestrated waitstaff. I couldn't stop staring at Andrew, our host for the evening, when he spoke, he was mesmerizing, he was beautiful in the way he detailed the food. Picture David Byrne with a Rod Sterling voice. It's almost as if a curtain opens up when a plate is introduced and placed in front of you, like you almost want to clap and yell, "bravo!" A few more glasses of champagne, i just might have. If you haven't been to Dankos, consider it or you're missing out on a culinary treat. I love you Gary, thank you, it was special last night, for sure, see you again Gary? Soon.

Although this wasn't my first time at Gary Danko, I felt compelled to write a review after reading about the less than stellar experience from other Yelpers. Our party of 7 basically tried 80% of the menu (fewer desserts) and everything was delectable. From the glazed oysters, rock shrimp risotto, and seared tuna to the lemon pepper duck, Thai seafood curry, pork, and scallops. Service was also impeccable and the evening was pure joy. Dining here was my first Michelin Star experience and it was incredible!! I came here for a celebration with my boyfriend and we both got 4 courses ($101, from any part of the menu) and shared it. Between us we got 2 appetizers, 3 seafood dishes, 2 meat entrees, and 1 dessert. Things I'd recommend: Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Pumpkin, Shimeji Mushrooms and Sage: This was AMAZING. There was a LOT of seafood in it, and it was so creamy and delicious. Definitely recommend! Pan Seared Bass: The bass was so tender! The succotash underneath was also perfect, really nice contrast of texture. Roast Maine Lobster: Also amazing. The lobster was so tender and the chantarelle mushrooms were so flavorful, I wish there were more of them! Pan Seared Scallops: Favorite of the night for sure!! I'm super tempted to come back and get a 5 course meal of just 5 rounds of scallops. Everything on the plate was so delicious and scallops were PERFECT. They were seared and crispy on the outside but so soft/tender on the inside. SO GOOD. I think I might be a little biased because I like seafood a lot more than I like meat, but I felt like all the seafood dishes/appetizers were better than the meat entrees! The meat entrees were good but they were pretty heavy/rich. The service was incredible. All the servers were so friendly and the food was timed perfectly: right after ordering an amuse-bouche came out to take the edge off the hunger, and all the courses were timed in such a fashion that right after you finished the previous, you had enough time to digest and converse. In the EXACT MOMENT when you started thinking about the next course, it would just appear, like magic. Overall it was an amazing experience. Definitely will try to come again!

Honestly, writing a review for Gary Danko two months after my visit is a bit tough. There were so many amazing elements (and courses) and I feel like without going into detail on each menu item I tried that I am doing the business a disservice. Having said that, the benefit of waiting is that all excess floury content has boiled off and I'm left with a beautiful velvety review reduction which is succinct, complex and easy to digest amidst the literal thousands of reviews already written. The venue is extremely posh, geared towards a fine dining experience. The soft lighting and music, the fragrant smells of the food, and the low hum of table talk almost give you a cosy shiver the moment you walk in. The service here from top to bottom was equally excellent from the host upon arrival to the bartender who made us drinks when we arrived, the sommelier who recommended not only great wines but excellent pre-dinner cocktails and to the endless number of servers who touched our table at one point or another to ensure we were taken care of. At GD you have the choice of buying off menu single courses or doing one of several levels of tasting menus which incorporate any number of courses you'd like (you can have 4 appetizers a main and a dessert or 1 of each, etc, etc. Additionally, you can ask for the wine pairing menu which the sommelier then works to pair your previously mentioned choices with 2-4oz wine tastings that work with each dish. I went with the wine pairings and if I recall a 6-course dinner option. I won't go into every dish but the general consensus from our table (and my own experience) was that every course was picture perfect and delicious. The other consistent opinion amongst our group was that even when not doing the tasting menus the courses were very small, at times no more than 2-3 bites tops. I understand this is fine dining but with the wallet hit I wasn't quite satiated to the point I would have liked. The wine pairings were exceptional, if you're contemplating this as an option then do it 100%, it's an experience all on it's own. Great wines, and it's paired so well that you'd think the wine was made just for that dish (or vice versa). Aside from the mild (very mild) disappointment with portion size the experience was tops. I'm likely not meant for fine dining as I like being full when pay $350 for a meal. Eatcrest Out

    Restaurant Gary Danko was delicious and you won't leave hungry.  We got the three course meal for $89.  I had the (1) risotto with rock shrimp, crab, asparagus and beech mushrooms, (2) roast main lobster, and (3) filet of beef with potato gnocchi.  My boyfriend had the (1) Coconut Thai curry with shrimp, calamari, lobster, scallops, and mushrooms, (2) filet of beef, and (3) creme fraiche cheesecake.  We had two drinks each and the bill with tip, taxes, and whatever else CA and SF add ended up around $350.  So know what you're getting into before you go so that you don't have a horrible surprise when you leave!

    I like that you can customize your 3, 4, or 5 courses - choosing from any section of the menu.  Meaning, you could get 4 options from the dessert section or 3 filets of beef if you so choose.  I'm not a dessert person and was thrilled to not be forced to have that as a course as so many other places do.  They will modify the portion sizing depending on what you are ordering.  So if you get two appetizers and a filet, the filet will be larger in size than if you were to get two other meat options with the filet.

    In my opinion, the gnocchi was the best thing I tasted.  I would have preferred all gnocchi and no filet!  The steak was okay.  My boyfriend who is not as into food as I am raved about the cheesecake and actually called his meal "out of this world."  A phrase I don't believe I've ever heard him utter.

    We were happy with the portion sizes - its not like the commercial of the couple who go to the fancy restaurant and have to stop at the convenience store on the way home to get more food.  But, considering you're paying $30 for each course, you should be full!

    Nice touch to send everyone home with a wonderful pineapple sponge cake for the next day.  Delicious!!

    No jacket required for men, but dress up anyways and have a great night out!

    1 check-in

    One of the best dining experiences EVER. My expectations were pretty high going in as we were able to dine at Daniel in NYC earlier this year and I was also a little weary of the prior reviews that mentioned Danko maybe slipping a little bit. My verdict? Nothing short of FANTASTIC. Bookmark this restaurant and make a reservation for your next trip in SF.

    That being said, reservations may be hard to come by. The booking window opens 2 months (not 60 days) prior to the date you are looking for. The difference of 2 months vs 60 days is huge because it means you may or may not get in at the date/time you prefer. The best way to make reservations is to call right the restaurant directly. Danko is on OpenTable, however they offer very limited slots via OpenTable. Also, be sure to note a special occasions upon making your reservation.

    We arrived and checked in with the hostess. We were a little early and started our evening at the bar. The cocktail menu is comprised of classic drinks, I had a Kir Royale and my bf had a Manhattan, both perfectly crafted. The restaurant is a good size with an intimate and romantic feel.

    After moving to our table, we made our dinner selections. There a few different ways you can order, either Chef's tasting menu ($128 for 5 courses with optional $95 wine pairings) or choose your own from their extensive options of appetizers, seafood, meat, and dessert. If you choose your own, you can pick 3 courses ($89), 4 courses ($109), or 5 courses ($128). They also don't limit the types of courses you can get, so you can order all entrees or all desserts if you wanted. Wine pairings are not offered if you select your own courses.

    Both my bf and I selected 5 courses and between the two of us we had:
    - seared foie gras with caramelized onions and apples
    - dungeness crab salad with avocado, citrus, quinoa
    - seared ahi with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms
    - porcini and mushroom bique
    - branzini with fennel puree and nicoise olives
    - seared scallop with butternut fondue, braised leeks, carrot-parsnip puree
    - herb crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, medjool dates, rainbow carrots, and green chermoula
    - juniper crusted bison with trumpet mushrooms, cipollini mushrooms, and herb spatzle
    - artisanal cheese course (you pick 4 from their cart) and served with raisin bread and fruit
    - grand marnier souffle with blood orange sorbet
    - bonus dessert : chocolate tart, presented for our anniversary

    AND IT WAS ALLLLL DELICIOUS!! I'll spare the nitty gritties of each dish and just say that each dish was cooked to perfection, well balanced and seasoned. The dishes that stood out to me most were the porcini bisque, lamb, and bison...probably only because it's not something you come across on every menu. Their menu is also always changing, so it can be hard to order based on recommended dishes mentioned in reviews. I think the best way to enjoy your dining experience is to share bites from each other like we did so that you are able to try a little bit of everything. If you normally have a pretty healthy appetite, you will have no issues with 5 courses. There are also a few extras in between in the courses like the amuse-bouche, bread service, and a cake for you take home for breakfast. The service was also flawless, with wine flowing and waters always full.

    A few things I'd also like to mention...
    1. While I am an avid Yelper and normally make my bf wait so I can snap photos of our meal before we eat, please put your phone away and just enjoy your experience and the company you are with. The only reason I even took a photo of my souffle was because of its amazing height (though hard to see). The couple that was seated next us were THOSE people as the gf insisted on 5 different photos of just her and her first course and then proceeded to photograph her bf and his dish. It's one thing to take a quick photo, but don't be a distraction and have a full on photo shoot
    2. The dining experience at Gary Danko is slightly less formal than other Michelin-star, fine dining restaurants (like Daniel) so one cannot make equal comparisons. I would consider the attire to be business casual because let's be real, we're in Cali. I also noticed they don't implement a couple service nuances (like synchronized service), which makes the experience less formal, not a bad thing, just an observation
    3. I did not think portions were small as mentioned in the couple reviews I read. I actually thought each dish was a pretty fair portion for fine dining and considering that dinner is multiple courses
    4. When you are leaving, you can ask for a copy of the menu from that night's service. It's presented in a gold envelope and signed by Chef Danko, makes for a great keepsake :)

    Just like any other Yelper, I have been putting off going to this popular restaurant in the city FOREVER, because there are too many other good fine dining spots around. I finally got around to going the other night since I was in the city at the time and we got pretty lucky with just walking in and no reservations.

    Gary Danko is located on North Point Street in the Russian Hill neighborhood of San Francisco. It's in a very touristy area (by Fisher's Wharf.) so I was kind of put off by that piece of information. The parking situation isn't  very good because of that. You might have to drive around for a while trying to find a spot or you can always use their valet service at the front entrance for a fee of $20.

    I think I may have been spoiled by the many other fine dining establishments I've tried, but for some reason, I just wasn't blown away by the food and cocktails. I was expecting more from a restaurant with a Michelin Star and an average of 4 1/2 stars. Don't get me wrong, I do think the value is great when it comes to price versus amount. Customers can pick from ordering a 3, 4, or 5 course Tasting Menu and they can also customize whichever dishes they want i.e. 1 appetizer and 2 entrées without dessert. They also give a extra dessert if customers are celebrating a special event. On top of that, they also send over an extra plate of mini desserts. When you are given the bill at the end of the night, you are also given their special house-made cake to take home with you. The service at the restaurant was good. I saw servers doing the "sweeping" of the tables often throughout the night.

    While I did taste each dish and finished each morsel of food on the plates, it felt like food I could've ordered at any other American restaurant. It just didn't seem that refined to me although it was good. None of the flavors were creative or innovative, even the Soufflé which I was eagerly waiting for at the end of the meal was too dense (cakey) and completely deflated within seconds. For the price we paid, I would probably rather pick to go dine at Alexander's Steakhouse. Their light and airy Soufflés just can't be replicated. Overall, I was glad I finally got the chance to dine at Gary Danko. I would go back if we had any events to celebrate with friends. (Seems like each table was celebrating something.)

    Honestly, writing a review for Gary Danko two months after my visit is a bit tough. There were so many amazing elements (and courses) and I feel like without going into detail on each menu item I tried that I am doing the business a disservice.

    Having said that, the benefit of waiting is that all excess floury content has boiled off and I'm left with a beautiful velvety review reduction which is succinct, complex and easy to digest amidst the literal thousands of reviews already written.

    The venue is extremely posh, geared towards a fine dining experience. The soft lighting and music, the fragrant smells of the food, and the low hum of table talk almost give you a cosy shiver the moment you walk in.

    The service here from top to bottom was equally excellent from the host upon arrival to the bartender who made us drinks when we arrived, the sommelier who recommended not only great wines but excellent pre-dinner cocktails and to the endless number of servers who touched our table at one point or another to ensure we were taken care of.

    At GD you have the choice of buying off menu single courses or doing one of several levels of tasting menus which incorporate any number of courses you'd like (you can have 4 appetizers a main and a dessert or 1 of each, etc, etc. Additionally, you can ask for the wine pairing menu which the sommelier then works to pair your previously mentioned choices with 2-4oz wine tastings that work with each dish.

    I went with the wine pairings and if I recall a 6-course dinner option. I won't go into every dish but the general consensus from our table (and my own experience) was that every course was picture perfect and delicious. The other consistent opinion amongst our group was that even when not doing the tasting menus the courses were very small, at times no more than 2-3 bites tops. I understand this is fine dining but with the wallet hit I wasn't quite satiated to the point I would have liked.

    The wine pairings were exceptional, if you're contemplating this as an option then do it 100%, it's an experience all on it's own. Great wines, and it's paired so well that you'd think the wine was made just for that dish (or vice versa).

    Aside from the mild (very mild) disappointment with portion size the experience was tops. I'm likely not meant for fine dining as I like being full when pay $350 for a meal.

    Eatcrest Out
